Clover does not measure code coverage for class fields initialization lines. See attached screenshot. Possible implementation:

1) for static fields (class scope)

All static fields are being initialized when class is loaded by classloader. Thus Clover could remember a list source regions with static fields in clover.db and add single static initialization block in a class containing a boolean flag. If class is loaded then it would set flag to true (we could assume that all fields were initialized as well).

2) for non-static fields (instance scope)

All non-static fields are being initialized when instance is created by a constructor call. Thus clover could remember a list of source regions with static fields in clover.db and add a code marker to every class constructor. This marker would set the flag to true. 


Draft example:

{code:java}
class Abc {

   static int a = 0;

   int b = 1;

   Abc() {

   }

   Abc(int x) { 

   }
}
{code}

Clover would do sth like:

{code:java}
class Abc {
   static {
     __CLV.CLASS_INITIALZED =true;
   }

   static int a = 0;    // covered 1 time = (CLASS_INITIALIZED == true)

   int b = 1;           // covered N times = (INSTANCE_INC)

   Abc() {
     __CLV.INSTANCE_INC(); // i.e. we count number of instances created
   }

   Abc(int x) { 
     __CLV.INSTANCE_INC();
   }
}
{code}

Having a following piece of code using a Java7 multiple-catch language feature:

{code:java}
try { 
   //...
} catch (FirstException|SecondException e) {
  throw e;
}
{code}

Clover will make code instrumentation like this:
{code:java}
} catch (FirstException|SecondException e) {
    __CLR3_1_6cch31flqx6.R.inc(28);throw e;
}
{code}

The problem is that we know that exception was caught, be we don't know whether it was FirstException or SecondException type. Clover does not support branch coverage in catch statements. 

I would be nice to have this information as well, similarly as we've got in conditional expressions, like:

{code:java}
if (exceptionName.equals("First"))
{code}

is being translated to:
{code:java}
if ((((exceptionName.equals("First"))&&
(__CLR3_1_6cch31flqx6.R.iget(24)!=0|true))||
(__CLR3_1_6cch31flqx6.R.iget(25)==0&false))) 
{code}

Clover instrumenter does not handle the @SuppressWarnings annotation placed before exception type in the catch clause. See following examples:

{noformat}
protected void testWithAnnotation() throws IOException {
  try {
  //FAILS
  } catch (@SuppressWarnings("unused") RuntimeException ioe) { }
}


protected void testWithoutAnnotation() throws IOException {
  try {
  // OK
  } catch (RuntimeException ioe) { }
}
{noformat}
